    "body": "This is expected default behaviour, in my opinion - for example, similar `str.contains()` also returns `NaN` for any non-string values.\r\n\r\nHowever, I think you're right that there is scope for a feature to improve this method. `str.contains()` has a parameter `na` which can be used to control the output on non-string values. If you set `na=False` you get `False` instead of `NaN`. I would suggest adding a similar parameter to `str.isalpha()`, for example:\r\n\r\n```python\r\nimport pandas as pd\r\nimport numpy as np\r\n\r\ntest_series = pd.Series(['one', 1, 2, np.nan, 'five'])\r\n\r\ntest_series.str.isalpha()\r\n# Returns:\r\n# Out[7]: \r\n# 0    True\r\n# 1     NaN\r\n# 2     NaN\r\n# 3     NaN\r\n# 4    True\r\n# dtype: object\r\n\r\ntest.str.isalpha(na=False)\r\n# Currently returns:\r\n# TypeError: wrapper() got an unexpected keyword argument 'na'\r\n# ---\r\n# Should return:\r\n# Out[7]: \r\n# 0     True\r\n# 1    False\r\n# 2    False\r\n# 3    False\r\n# 4     True\r\n# dtype: object\r\n```"
  },
